Subject: [sfraves] bsp: Saturday! [KONTROL] w/ Traum/Trapez/MBF founder TRIPLE R (Cologne, Germany)

For a small taste of what you're in for, check out the free mixes below.
There's also a pretty interesting interview from Resident Advisor worth
checking out.

But when listening, keep in mind, those mixes are made up of only songs fro=
m
his own labels!  When he plays for us Saturday, he'll have his entire
arsenal of tracks he's come across in his 20 years as a DJ (including 7
years behind the counter at KOMPAKT) at his disposal.

This will be Riley's long overdue West Coast debut and one of only 2 US
appearances, and he's coming ready to blow the roof off the Endup!

Expect no less than finely-crafted, beautiful minimal and maximal techno
that's as fun to listen to as it is to dance to.

This man is truly a dance music legend.  Do yourself a favor and don't miss
this one!

____________________________________________________



Saturday, August 2nd, 2008

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant-house
every 1st Saturday @ The Endup


featuring from Cologne, Germany
in an exclusive appearance:

TRIPLE R   (aka Riley Reinhold)

Traum . Trapez . MBF . Kompakt


Riley Reinhold, best known as Triple R, has been a hugely
influential figure in Germany's dance music culture for nearly
20 years.  Starting off as a DJ at early illegal parties in his
native Cologne, he soon found himself writing for top music
mags (including his own De:Bug) before going on to co-found
the revered labels Traum, Trapez, and MBF.  Between his
years at the Kompakt record shop, developing talent for his
5 labels, residencies at Cologne's best clubs, a radio show,
and organizing monthly parties, it's no wonder he's
practically considered a national treasure.  This month we
are thrilled to share some of the riches with San Francisco
with an extended West Coast debut set.


with special guest:

CHRISTIAN MORA (bang the box)


and [KONTROL] residents:

ALLAND BYALLO  (nightlight music . auralism . leibe*detail)
NIKOLA BAYTALA  (s.w.a.t . robsoul . junior boys own)
CRAIG KUNA  (platform . esdjco)


____________________________________________________


The ENDUP
401 6th St @ Harrison, SF
10pm - 6am / 21+ / $15
http://www.theendup.com

FREE until 11pm!

___________________________________________________


TRIPLE R (aka Riley Reinhold)

Riley Reinhold (aka Triple R) is part owner of the Traum Schallplatten
family of labels encompassing Traum, Trapez and MBF. He started DJing in
1984 in Cologne and later on at electronic dance parties in 1989. Together
with Sascha K=F6sch (now Chief Editor of De:BUG) the pair assembled their o=
wn
sound system in 1990, playing at early techno, house and acid parties at
every club and party imaginable (both legal and illegal) throughout Cologne
and beyond.

>From 1991 to 1993 Riley belonged to the early Force Inc DJ team, together
with Ian Pooley, Tonka, T.P. Heckmann (Live), and Alec Empire, playing at
big clubs in Switzerland and Austria. He was resident at the legendary
Elektro club in Berlin 1993 in the company of DJs such as Robert Hood, Dave
Clarke, Kotai. Later he DJed at its successor, the Panasonic club. He was
also resident at Ego in Dusseldorf, with Florian from Kraftwerk a regular i=
n
the crowd.

In 1994 he was sent to London to meet the Aphex Twin and write an article
about the vast emerging breakbeat scene in London together with Sascha
K=F6sch. His record reviews and articles in the biggest german indie mag SP=
EX
and later Frontpage (an icon for techno culture in Berlin) from 1994 to 199=
8
earned him an international reputation as a journalist which later resulted
in the formation of his own magazine De:BUG.

For the last three years, Riley has been resident DJ at the largest techno
club in Cologne, Sensor, playing with guests such as Swayzak, Carl Craig,
Daniel Bell, Thomas Brinkmann, Miss Kittin, Richie Hawtin, Magda, Green
Velvet, Markus Nikolai, Alter Ego, Steve Bug, Luciano and Broker/ Dealer. H=
e
also plays occasionally at Camouflage together with Sascha K=F6sch and has
been offered a residency at Subway in Cologne. More recently, Riley has bee=
n
hosting a new monthly night called MBF CLUB since June 2005.

Riley was involved for seven years at the Kompakt record store but quit in
2004 to concentrate on his labels Traum, Trapez and MBF together with
Jacqueline Klein.

___________________________________________________


CHRISTIAN MORA

Christian's story has only begun to be written. After getting his start in
1995, he began to make a name for himself by playing undergound parties,
mantaining residencies, and organizing full-moon parties all across Mexico.
After making the move to San Francisco in 2000, he started working at the
now defunct Nemesis distributor, helping to service dance music stores
across the states as well as his own store Crescent Records in Guadalajara.
By melding house, tech house, techno and electro into his own signature
blend, his good ear and taste for music has allowed him to DJ not only in
Mexico, but Spain, Holland, Japan and the States. For the last couple of
years, Christian as been playing club and underground events as a member of
Bang The Box, alongside fellow San Franciscans Solar, Lance DeSardi, and
Guada. Previous Bang The Box guests have included John Tejada, Dan Curtin,
Jona, Dollz At Play, Alexkid, and Mr. C., with many more on the horizon.

http://www.myspace.com/bangtheboxsf

$15 @ the door
21+ w/id


15 DJs in 3 dance areas, Live Fire Dancing and POI on stage, Live
Vocalists, Percussionists, a OPEN Sangria Bar from 9-10pm, a whole bunch
of lovely party-going people, & it's all located at the greatest club in
SF! You couldn't ask for much more than what we've got in store for you,
and "Who's bringin' all of this madness?" you might ask? It's none other
than the delinquents from Pink Mammoth, Bassyx, and Evil Breaks. We're
teaming up to bring you our biggest party of the summer, "BIG BADA BOOM"!
There are a limited number of really cheap pre-sales ($5-$10), so you
might want to consider snagging one before they go up.


The DJ's:

Aaron Jae (Space Cowboys/Evil Breaks)
Syd Gris (Opel/Opulent Temple)
DRC (Mizumo Music)
Aaron Pope (Deep End/Bassyx)
Tamo
DJ Kimani
DJ Gunz
M.O.D.
Ace Tatsu
Dex Stakker
Derek Hena
Jonathan W.
Moe Moe and more!


The Live Performers:

PM Collective with live percussion by &D and Jandro, along with vocals by
Krystle Jones!!
Live Fire Dancing w/Jaden Rose
Live POI w/Robyn Drysdale

Subject: [sfraves] Text message spam from Prismatic on my cell phone

Anyone else getting it?  I'm not sure how my PHONE got on their list,  
but I've been getting it from them for some time.  I wouldn't mind  
being on their email list... I'd just set a rule to filter to my BSP  
folder and all... but I can't exactly do that with SMS and I'm trying  
to avoid having to up my text plan and pay more for the higher tiers.

Since Prismatic is local, and there are a few familiar names from  
SFRaves in the messages, I figured I'd ask here if anyone is familiar  
or affiliated with them enough to know if texting "remove" back, as  
they suggest, will be respected; or if, as with email spam, replying  
in any way just lets them know there's a live address there and I'd be  
dooming myself to 10x as much spam?

Thanks!


cya,
john

On Sun, 3 Aug 2008, Ray Wong wrote:
-&e->I'd be pretty sure they'll respect.  They're all event announcements,
-&e->there've just been more "other" prismatic related events than there
-&e->have been tonal parties lately...  At least, I've only gotten a handful
-&e->each month, have't been that many I've noticed, and they were all events.

WRONG. A lot of people have sold email lists in this scene over the years, 
and it's fucking annoying.  I've *never* signed up for any list knowingly, 
but the email address I use for this list, as well as the spamtrip address 
I gave Nitevibe's THE DJ LIST have been sold to every fucker up and down 
the cali coast.  It's illegal as of 2003, and even the lists you WANT to 
be on should have a forced Opt-In every 6 months BY LAW (i.e. the default 
list management behavior is to purge the list every 6 months, and include 
directions for staying on if you wish to continue).

Hint:  I think DJ Seven, Dmitri Mykonos, ultralounges, any party 
containing the line "women *** before ***" and other boring sexist drivel, 
etc are all shit for their policies on sending unsolicited email to 
addresses they got through shady shit, I'd never leave the house for that, 
EVER.  A couple people/crews I let slide (people I know in person who 
might have thought it best to keep me up to date), but lately I've been 
taking care of matters taking in the role of being my own ISP and 
complaining via phone (expensive for them, and fun for me when I wake up 
cranky) to their email list service providers (usually ends up in a fine, 
or "points" against the cleanliness of their lists).

-&e->It's not like there's THAT many folks in Prismatic...

It only takes one asshole with no respect for others to spam thousands, 
even millions.  Prismatic should come correct (and yeah, they sent me 
mail, again, couldn't fucking imagine why I'd want that shit so EAT A DICK 
SPAMMERS), as well as any other crew that can't figure out that people who 
didn't ask to be on a list won't likely hold whatever they send in the 
highest regard.  It's shit promotion, usually for sub-par events, and 
these people need to start getting wise to the fact that it's never 
worked, it's never been "ok" to just send me an update every couple weeks, 
let alone nowadays.

As for John's scenario, I'd recommend getting as much info as you can 
regarding the source of those SMS's and going into ream mode.  It might be 
just a tad annoying on a per person basis, but remember you're likely 
speaking for a couple hundred people just like you when you complain (that 
might not know how to deal with unsolicited email... let alone SMS, that's 
just fucking tacky).

And if you think I'm mean about this shit, I lived in Salt Lake City Utah 
for a year, and used to get missionaries a couple times a week.  And then 
they stopped.  It's as if my answering the door in my boxers smoking a 
cigarette and holding a bottle of tequila, playing Lard or Skinny Puppy on 
my stereo and begging them to come into the basement in my best pervert 
voice rather than talking in the living room let them know I wasn't ready 
for the good news...  Sorry, but again, these might be nice people, they 
might really believe in what they have to say, they might even want to 
save me from eternal damnation, but it's my fucking door on my fucking 
house wasting my fucking time.

andyw

p.s.	And yes, it's possible I do in fact need a hug, going through a 
shitty breakup.  :(

User-Agent: Mutt/1.5.13 (2006-08-11)

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Text message spam from Prismatic on my cell phone


On Mon, Aug 04, 2008 at 12:32:39AM -0700, AndyW wrote:
> 
> On Sun, 3 Aug 2008, Ray Wong wrote:
> -&e->I'd be pretty sure they'll respect.  They're all event announcements,
> -&e->there've just been more "other" prismatic related events than there
> -&e->have been tonal parties lately...  At least, I've only gotten a handful
> -&e->each month, have't been that many I've noticed, and they were all events.
> 
> WRONG. A lot of people have sold email lists in this scene over the years, 

Not wrong.  We're talking about SMS messages, not email.  While there are
usually email->SMS gateways, there's no good way to automatically figure
out which cell #s need to go to which email gateways (every provider
maintains their own and they won't forward between each other).  None
of your examples have any known correlation to the SMS service that
Prismatic uses.  Having implemented SMS detection systems, I'm quite
sure how hard this is.  

OTOH, if you actually followed the directions on a tonal announcement that
said to text "prismatic" to the 5 digit # for the service for info, you
did sign up for the general prismatic list, not a single infor request for
a tonal party.  That part wasn't so clear in the instructions, but considering
I did the same thing and haven't gotten anything but other prismatic info,
I'm ready to say they haven't yet sold my # to any SMS spammers.  

Email spam is separate from SMS.  Yeah, they need to correct any email
spam they've facilitated, but they're still technologically different issues.

If you're going to fight spam, you need to stay rational or you're just
going to sabotage your own efforts.  I've been involved in the technology
for fighting spam for almost 10 years, and can guarantee that ranting like
you just did WILL NOT WORK.

And yes, have a hug.  sucks when things don't work out.  Pretty sure spammers
aren't to blame for your breakup unless you actually tried to buy those
penis enlargement pills or something, though. :) 

-R.

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

References: <7A57C7BF-45B9-4727-A178-23A7F3757446@gmail.com> <20080803194838.GN6323@jmmredux.doomba.com> <Pine.LNX.4.62.0808040004420.19260@atari> <20080804161408.GQ6323@jmmredux.doomba.com>
Date: Mon, 4 Aug 2008 14:28:36 -0700
Message-ID: <001801c8f679$0f567860$6501a8c0@apo>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain;
	charset="us-ascii"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
X-Mailer: Microsoft Office Outlook 11
In-Reply-To: <20080804161408.GQ6323@jmmredux.doomba.com>
X-MimeOLE: Produced By Microsoft MimeOLE V6.00.2900.3198
Thread-Index: Acj2TbM7Q/I3rJvlTOemcOoZWOLnAAAKGMkg
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: RE: [sfraves] Text message spam from Prismatic on my cell phone

Hey alls, I am Prismatic, I'm the the sole owner the business, so anything
you get from Prismatic is from me.

The Prismatic text list is run through msgme.com, my email list is run
through Mobile Storm, there are unsubscribe details at the bottom of all
messages be it text or email.

The text list was built up through: discount signup for the Tonal parties
(which explicitly asks you if you want to confirm adding your number to the
Prismatic list), online signup, and clipboard signup at Tonal and my other
parties.

The email list was built off of porting over my old and now defunkt
djandrewphelan.com list as well as online and clipboard signup.

I've never sold/traded emails or phone numbers collected with anyone else.
To me it's bad business, you end up alienating a lot of people who are
annoyed by it, and you end up spending a lot of money sending messages out
to people that don't want to receive them.

Tonal will still be happening, though not as frequently as in the past, as
it's gotten very hard for us to aqquire reasonably sized, secure underground
venues recently, and both Eric and myself are a lot busier than we were last
year.  The result has been more small one off undergrounds and more club
events, as we want to make sure we don't attach the Tonal name to a party
unless we can really do it up right.

-Andrew

> -----Original Message-----
> From: Ray Wong [mailto:rayw@rayw.net]
> Sent: Monday, August 04, 2008 9:14 AM
> To: AndyW
> Cc: Ray Wong; John B.; SFRaves Laser Outpost'
> Subject: Re: [sfraves] Text message spam from Prismatic on my cell phone

> 
> On Mon, Aug 04, 2008 at 12:32:39AM -0700, AndyW wrote:
> >
> > On Sun, 3 Aug 2008, Ray Wong wrote:
> > -&e->I'd be pretty sure they'll respect.  They're all event
> announcements,
> > -&e->there've just been more "other" prismatic related events than there
> > -&e->have been tonal parties lately...  At least, I've only gotten a
> handful
> > -&e->each month, have't been that many I've noticed, and they were all
> events.
> >
> > WRONG. A lot of people have sold email lists in this scene over the
> years,
> 
> Not wrong.  We're talking about SMS messages, not email.  While there are
> usually email->SMS gateways, there's no good way to automatically figure
> out which cell #s need to go to which email gateways (every provider
> maintains their own and they won't forward between each other).  None
> of your examples have any known correlation to the SMS service that
> Prismatic uses.  Having implemented SMS detection systems, I'm quite
> sure how hard this is.
> 
> OTOH, if you actually followed the directions on a tonal announcement that
> said to text "prismatic" to the 5 digit # for the service for info, you
> did sign up for the general prismatic list, not a single infor request for
> a tonal party.  That part wasn't so clear in the instructions, but
> considering
> I did the same thing and haven't gotten anything but other prismatic info,
> I'm ready to say they haven't yet sold my # to any SMS spammers.
> 
> Email spam is separate from SMS.  Yeah, they need to correct any email
> spam they've facilitated, but they're still technologically different
> issues.
> 
> If you're going to fight spam, you need to stay rational or you're just
> going to sabotage your own efforts.  I've been involved in the technology
> for fighting spam for almost 10 years, and can guarantee that ranting like
> you just did WILL NOT WORK.
> 
> And yes, have a hug.  sucks when things don't work out.  Pretty sure
> spammers
> aren't to blame for your breakup unless you actually tried to buy those
> penis enlargement pills or something, though. :)
> 
> -R.
> 
>

> For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: Re: [sfraves] The 5 Greatest Things Ever Accomplished While High

good point about huxley. although crick isn't the only one to thought of 
the prehistoric alien thing. and crick might actually be right. 
scientists actually now believe that all life was possibly spawned from 
bacteria riding on comets crashing into planets like coconuts landing on 
sandy beaches in the Caribbean or Polynesia. which could actually mean 
that there are more of us out there than we think. life doesn't have to 
be intelligent to exist. extra terrestrials can be real and they don't 
necessarily have to follow the physics of this planet to exist.. take 
chemosynthetic bacteria for example. possibly the real reasons why there 
are no UFOs is because the chance of there being intelligent life 
capable of travelling at the speed of light, and/or the possibility 
there being aliens being existing at the same time as us, in the 
fraction of a second of time in the universe that our lives are, is very 
very slim (one in a 100 billion sayeth the Sagan). although i think we 
are pretty ego driven to believe that we are a special life force; we 
just happen to be lucky enough to produce cognitive thought.

food for human thought.
sean.

A February 24, 2005, Washington Post article begins:

There's nothing exotic or complicated about how phenoms are made in  
Washington, and, more to the point, how they are broken.

"Andy Warhol said we all get our 15 minutes of fame," says Barack  
Obama. "I've already had an hour and a half. I mean, I'm so  
overexposed, I'm making Paris Hilton look like a recluse."

That is pretty much the who and the why of Sen. McCain's explanation  
of his ad, is it not? It turns out he wasn't mocking Sen. Obama so  
much as channeling him. Or making a mini-documentary out of the Post's  
article.

Obama. "I've already had an hour and a half. I mean, I'm so  
overexposed, I'm making Paris Hilton look like a recluse."

That is pretty much the who and the why of Sen. McCain's explanation  
of his ad, is it not? It turns out he wasn't mocking Sen. Obama so  
much as channeling him. Or making a mini-documentary out of the Post's  
article.
>
>
>
> -- 
> San Francisco Bay Guardian's Readers Choice Award Winner: Best Radio  
> DJ:
> http://www.sfbg.com/promo/pollpositions.php
> AIM: jckzsu (or kzsudj during my show.)
>
> "Opinions are my own only, and do not necessarily represent those of
> KZSU Radio or Stanford University." (or words to that effect.)

the world who tries to make us uncomfortable."
-Hunter S. Thompson

while you are alive!  What you call "salvation" belongs to the time  
before death.  If you don't break your ropes while you are alive, do  
you think ghosts will do it after?"

George, I've anguished over this Obama thing.

I started writing a long explanation of my disillusionment with the  
Obama campaign but I don't want to open sfraves to the same type of  
irrational Obamamania that drove me from RG.  As far as I'm concerned  
Obama is the most divisive politician I've seen in my life.

To be brief I'm a "progressive" I guess.  But I'm not a "latte  
liberal."  I like my coffee strong and black with a touch of honey.   
And I have a low tolerance for jive these days.  As far as I can see  
Obama's new politics is just the same old politics of expediency.  The  
"Money" is clearly behind him.

I'm a Green Party member and I'll vote for McKinney.  She gives me a  
tingle up my leg, ya know?:)

I'll leave you with this:

Obama and the Empire

By William Blum

I'm afraid that if Barack Obama becomes president he's going to break  
a lot of young hearts. And some older ones as well.
http://www.informationclearinghouse.info/article20438.htm

this weekend is actually bangin. there's a couple campouts and there's a 
party in sac with ian lehman amber, dragn'fly, mek gamma and dirt. which 
i'd go to if i had wheels.
*Signal*
Techno :: Electro :: Electro House
August 9th, 2008

Featuring:



*Ian Lehman*
Live P.A. (Modern Recording Company, Audio Assault, Mankind,
Minneapolis)

Ian Lehman is one of the hottest emerging techno producers from the
United States. In 2001, he formed Abiotic Recordings with long-time
friend Dustin Zahn. He quickly moved on to release multiple solo
records on a plethora of labels such as Drumworks, Compound, Blueline,
Hidden Agenda, Audio Assault, and more. Together with Dustin Zahn he's
also formed 1/2 of The Attack People, whose releases span across labels
such as Abiotic and Mankind. Many producers these days do not have a
distinguishable sound, but this isn't the case for Ian Lehman. His
tracks are linear, dark, and heavily textured- DJ tools written
exclusively for techno's most daring DJs. Lets welcome him back after
an incredible performance at Stilldream 2007.



*Dj Amber*
(Sister, iamthedj. com 
<http://www.msplinks.com/MDFodHRwOi8vaWFtdGhlZGouY29t>, San Francisco)

Amber is a San Francisco-based techno dj and producer with a driving
beat and aggresively risky mixing technique in a town known for its
laid back house style. For over ten years she has brought her vigorous
style and enthusiastic stage presence to events throughout North
America and Europe.




*Dj Dragn'fly*
(dj4norml. org <http://www.msplinks.com/MDFodHRwOi8vZGo0bm9ybWwub3Jn>, 
Sacramento)

Known as a true "journey DJ", Dragn'fly possesses an uncanny ability to
read into the desires of the crowd and the diversity of each set
performed has provided Dragn'fly with the opportunity to headline
countless events. When not headlining under her own accord, Dragn'fly
acts as the strategic support for many event coordinators worldwide as
a key transitional DJ, opening or closing sets for the worlds
most-widely popular and renowned electronic music artists.
Dragn'fly incorporates an "aggressive-as-hell" mixing style with the
elements of funky electro, tech-trance and breaks; a combination that
has earned her a style that is uniquely hers. Her performances
repeatedly showcase a near frenzy of sound manipulation while she
tweaks her EQ's and shreds her vinyl, watching as her dancers rise and
fall to ecstatic pieces on the dance floor.

Also featuring:

*Dirt* Live P.A. (Omniscient Records, San Francisco)

*G.a.m.m.a.
* (Left Coast Techno, Stilldream, Sacramento)

*Mek* (Signal, Stilldream, Sacramento, Bday show!)

Details:

8P.M.-3A.M.
Drink Specials
18+/21+ to drink

this weekend is actually bangin. there's a couple campouts and there's a 
party in sac with ian lehman amber, dragn'fly, mek gamma and dirt. which 
i'd go to if i had wheels.
*Signal*
Techno :: Electro :: Electro House
August 9th, 2008

Featuring:



*Ian Lehman*
Live P.A. (Modern Recording Company, Audio Assault, Mankind,
Minneapolis)

Ian Lehman is one of the hottest emerging techno producers from the
United States. In 2001, he formed Abiotic Recordings with long-time
friend Dustin Zahn. He quickly moved on to release multiple solo
records on a plethora of labels such as Drumworks, Compound, Blueline,
Hidden Agenda, Audio Assault, and more. Together with Dustin Zahn he's
also formed 1/2 of The Attack People, whose releases span across labels
such as Abiotic and Mankind. Many producers these days do not have a
distinguishable sound, but this isn't the case for Ian Lehman. His
tracks are linear, dark, and heavily textured- DJ tools written
exclusively for techno's most daring DJs. Lets welcome him back after
an incredible performance at Stilldream 2007.



*Dj Amber*
(Sister, iamthedj. com 
<http://www.msplinks.com/MDFodHRwOi8vaWFtdGhlZGouY29t>, San Francisco)

Amber is a San Francisco-based techno dj and producer with a driving
beat and aggresively risky mixing technique in a town known for its
laid back house style. For over ten years she has brought her vigorous
style and enthusiastic stage presence to events throughout North
America and Europe.




*Dj Dragn'fly*
(dj4norml. org <http://www.msplinks.com/MDFodHRwOi8vZGo0bm9ybWwub3Jn>, 
Sacramento)

Known as a true "journey DJ", Dragn'fly possesses an uncanny ability to
read into the desires of the crowd and the diversity of each set
performed has provided Dragn'fly with the opportunity to headline
countless events. When not headlining under her own accord, Dragn'fly
acts as the strategic support for many event coordinators worldwide as
a key transitional DJ, opening or closing sets for the worlds
most-widely popular and renowned electronic music artists.
Dragn'fly incorporates an "aggressive-as-hell" mixing style with the
elements of funky electro, tech-trance and breaks; a combination that
has earned her a style that is uniquely hers. Her performances
repeatedly showcase a near frenzy of sound manipulation while she
tweaks her EQ's and shreds her vinyl, watching as her dancers rise and
fall to ecstatic pieces on the dance floor.

Also featuring:

*Dirt* Live P.A. (Omniscient Records, San Francisco)

*G.a.m.m.a.
* (Left Coast Techno, Stilldream, Sacramento)

*Mek* (Signal, Stilldream, Sacramento, Bday show!)

Details:

8P.M.-3A.M.
Drink Specials
18+/21+ to drink
$5 before 11, $8 after

if given a choice though i'd rather go with the candidate that has 
actually practiced constitutional law (the guy with the o in his name). 
because obviously the last president had no idea what the constitution 
or bill of rights was about. even still, if you're looking at the 
executive branch you should really look at it as one of the lesser 
branches of government (i'm sick of the president being regarded as a 
king and the monarchies handed down through the parties. take queen 
hillary or prince bush  for example), congress and the house still rule. 
if you really wanted a force to change the world, invest money in 
lobbyists and invest heavily.

anyway i put up an NRR on this awhile ago and nobody listened. the place 
for government or law in a raves list is irrelevant. even when there was 
a supposed crackdown.. still raves going on. i would agree with apollo 
that there should be less talk of obama on the list.. but i also would 
have to add we shouldn't  support any major political views other than 
what our own political views towards raves are. if you vote it should be

add to the discussion on this any more.

night as a student in highschool. i still can't forget the way she=20
burned *every last bit* of body hair off her body to laurie anderson's=20
'big science' album. unforgettable.

although my other opinion on the burning man festival is that if things=20
like this can happen, why can't more effort like this be put into=20
throwing projects like this all year long? i mean, why save your=20

burning man. make burning man happen here all the time. be creative all=20
the time. go nuts, be nude in your back yard. i don't know, go crazy and =

organize some insane crap.  do some performance art.. whatever. your=20
world is free to do what you want to do.

i think burning man lulls people into thinking they can only be creative =

its truly obvious that that doesn't have to be the case.

t yourself. this is not news.

giant sound camps are hardly underrepresented on the playa. i do think it's=
 a bit ungrateful for lorin to speak out so harshly against the event that =
essentially made his career (imo), but if a few of those raver-magnet sound=
 camps fell off the map i think burning man might actually benefit...if the=
 festival can even still be helped at this point. i wouldn't miss him or hi=
s mega-sized big name superstar driven DJ-worship tents at all. if anything=
 the playa could use many many less of those camps. it's gotten so boring a=
nd predictable that i'm sitting out what would have been my 9th year in a r=
ow. burning man was attractive because it was fresh and weird and dangerous=
. your standard club night transposed onto a desert landscape is none of th=
ose things, regardless of how dope your tracks are or how hard you worked.

-&e->--- Phillip Mispagel <phillip@viberation.com> wrote:
-&e->> I've never seen him play, but Forest says he's an amazing DJ
-&e->> and does really wicked stuff with CDJ-1000s.

Yeah, like play the same set night after night at pre/de compression 
events.  ZZzzzzzzz....

Da Stickmon Sed:
-&e->That's Jokenfold stuff, and was fairly lame, IMO.

Lorin's whining speaks volumes about both him and the festival.  The fact 
that he is making a stand about not getting free money for the repeat 
opportunity that pretty much made his career in the past is just an added 
irony bonus.

I think that the funding for arts projects should embrace those projects 
that are unique, but running into financial problems producing them to a 
scale that would benefit the event most.  Just 10 minutes walking on the 
playa would rank dance music sound systems as an "art form" NOT in need of 
additional development.  Along with blowing fire, poi, and EL wire they 
rank right at the bottom of forms of expression obviously needing 
support... they're doing just fine without help (and to many including 
myself, dance sound systems are the one thing they'd like to see *less* 
of).

Bassnectar, the BM LLC/BMORG/etc does not owe you shit, quit crying in 
your couscous.  If their decision pisses you and every other whack DJ and

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Bassnectar on Burning Man


J.C. <dougm@kzsu.stanford.edu> wrote:
> mo corleone wrote:

> > fund your own freaking sound camp. every organization has their set of
> > values and causes that they champion, and "sound art" in the way that
> > you and i mean it is not their focus. it's their festival so let them
> > fund what they want. if you don't like what you see out there then you
> > pay to bring it out yourself. this is not news.

Arts grants for "sound art" isn't such a whacky idea though... the thing
is, this would imply that they're curated.  Are you ready for musical
curation?  You get to convince a director of sound art that your angle
on music is new and interesting enough that you deserve special funding.

(I have a fantasy about booting the aging frat boys with "art cars"
blasting Classic Rock.)

> > giant sound camps are hardly underrepresented on the playa. i do think
> > it's a bit ungrateful for lorin to speak out so harshly against the
> > event that essentially made his career (imo), but if a few of those
> > raver-magnet sound camps fell off the map i think burning man might
> > actually benefit...

I might be inclined to agree -- except that I've already heard the
complaint that Burning Man has got more people going to fewer events.
Get rid of half of the rave camps and you'll either get double the
ravers packed into the half as much space, or a lot of disgruntled
ravers wandering around bugging other people.

Think of it like Fischerman's Wharf: you need some place to funnel
the clueless tourists.

> > if the festival can even still be helped at this point.

Now, now.  Remember: burning man is always dying.  It's always been
Better Before.

> > it's gotten so boring and predictable that i'm sitting out what
> > would have been my 9th year in a row.

I'm sitting one out just because doing Burning Man right can kind of
eat your life.  There's always another meeting to go to, another art
project to help slap together on a shoe-string...  I like to do other
stuff on occasion, and at present I'm helping out with Cellspace
(yes, putting energy into something local... odd thought, eh?).

> > burning man was attractive because it was fresh and weird and
> > dangerous.

Look for a different event.  They *are* out there, of course.

> I too was almost going to sit out this one as last year was a pretty
> off year

Didn't seem like it to me.  Serpent Mother, Big Rig Jig, Steampunk
Treehouse... Watching the temple burn from the tea temple was pretty
cool.  What would an "on" year look like?

> and what's happened in the intervening year hasn't been so great
> either.

They put the "trash tea temple" people in charge of the main temple
this year.  My main regret is not seeing how this works out:

  http://basurasagrada.org/concept/form/

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Bassnectar on Burning Man

Hey, couscous is awesome, b-hole!

I camped with Green Gorilla one year and heard a lot of this sort of "music is art, why doesn't music get funded, blah blah blah" puffery.  It does have a basis in reality- when you've schlepped half your world across the country year after year to help provide a wonderful time for so many people, and you hear of Joe Arts getting $10k for their interactive period blood fountain, it makes some sense that some of that same dough that we're all collectively "raising" through our "charitable donations" (tix sales) should go to help the sound folks out.

Those people (and me, in turn) worked harder to get that system and the domes, shade, infrastructure and general partyplex built and pimped than I would ever have imagined.  Most of the sound, lights and structures were already owned by somebody in the group, and the folks that owned all the stuff were nice enough to put it all in harms way for a week without it costing the collective a huge amount.  Each of us pitched in, I think, around $300 to help cover the cost of the trucks, structures, food, drink, etc, etc.  Grand total of around $30k, I think?

We ran a free bar and a huge sound system, crazy fire shows and lights, big chill area, for the better part of the week, had many thousands of guests.  Lots of fun.

The BMOrg could have given us $30k, but, then, was it really *that* difficult for each of us to come up with an extra couple hundred bucks?  They were up in our business to an almost comic level already- I'd sort of hate to see what they'd be like when they had a controlling interest in our shit.

Argh, I can't think this week, these are just musings,
-g

Da Stickmon Sed:

Lorin's whining speaks volumes about both him and the festival.  The fact 
that he is making a stand about not getting free money for the repeat 
opportunity that pretty much made his career in the past is just an added 
irony bonus.

I think that the funding for arts projects should embrace those projects 
that are unique, but running into financial problems producing them to a 
scale that would benefit the event most.  Just 10 minutes walking on the 
playa would rank dance music sound systems as an "art form" NOT in need of 
additional development.  Along with blowing fire, poi, and EL wire they 
rank right at the bottom of forms of expression obviously needing 
support... they're doing just fine without help (and to many including 
myself, dance sound systems are the one thing they'd like to see *less* 
of).

Bassnectar, the BM LLC/BMORG/etc does not owe you shit, quit crying in 
your couscous.  If their decision pisses you and every other whack DJ and 
faux fur ketamine clubber off the playa leaving something a little bit 
more interesting and diverse, I'd consider going again.

andyw

Subject: [sfraves] Think about doing an event at Cellspace?


As long as we're on the ever popular topic of "Burning Man vs.
The World", I thought I'd mention that Cellspace has got a bunch
of open dates in the upcoming weeks.  A lot of organizers are
running off to the desert, or are afraid that everyone else is --
if you've got an idea in mind for a cool event, take a look over
at:

  http://www.cellspace.org/new/node/5

Or just shoot us a proposal over at:

  events@cellspace.org

The art gallery up front is open right now, too, so there's potential
for events with an art tie-in.

(Tomorrow -- Friday, August 8th -- there's a fun one coming up:
"Action Figure and Friends": hard rock, aerialist, martial arts,
dance music, breakdancers, gallery art; all on a "superhero"
theme.)

On Thu, 7 Aug 2008, CHUCK G wrote:

-&e->I can't wait to tell people that YES, I HAVE gone to BM so they'll 
-&e->leave me the fuck alone about it. I'm pretty sure all of last year's 
-&e->40K+ attendees have asked me this. . .
-&e->
-&e->But apparently I'm 5 years too late anyways, as most people I know 
-&e->that have told me I "have to" go are not attending this year. =P
-&e->
-&e->BTW I'm playing at some center camp with a big Pong game on a movie 
-&e->screen or something. I don't know the name of it though, so there. 
-&e->Expect Electro (NOT!).

Oh god...

Does Electro have to get reamed on name-space too?  Electro originally 
meant blippy computery sounding breaks.  Kind of even before there was a 
breaks as a buyable genre (disco and funk records had breaks, but it was 
up to DJs to play just that part).  Now it's been claimed by that 
electro-house shit, which by the way sounds almost nothing like electro... 
its more like hardbag, or completely overproduced ADD techno with changes 
every couple bars and NRG noises, hoovers, nuschool/jungles basses and 
superfluous breakdowns.

"Electro" is properly defined as Aux88 or early Juan Atkins, or even some 
stuff by projects like Afrika Bam, Egyptian Lover, or Midnight Star 
(freakazoid) or Herbie Hancock's "Rocket".  It's breakdancing music 
muthafuckahz, not that playa scenster crap.  Press the eject on the 
boombox and give me the tape, I'm taking my cardboard, this is bullshit.

*sighs*
andyw

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Bassnectar on Burning Man



Alright, guess I'll throw my thoughts in the bucket, too.

I do have to wonder about anyone who bothers to complain about any event,
whether it be Burning Man or something else.  If you're going to go and
setup some exhibit, feel free, but what good does complaining do except
make you look like some ungrateful whiner?  So they didn't throw money
at you.  BFD.  The history of BM is replete with people falling in love
with it, and spending vast quantities of personal time and money to give
to that community.  Hell, especially here in SF, the dedication borders
on cultism.  We probably all know at least a few folks who basically now
do nothing but BM, BM decompression, and planning/work/fundraising for their
next BM.  Seems unhealthy, but it's their choice, and at least they've
found some cause for passion in life.  Go them.

As to the funding of sound camps vs other art, I perceive a bit of a
difference.  Most sound camps seem to spend the bulk of their (not camping
essentials) budget on gear.  This gear is reusable, and a lot of camps
seem to come away far better equipped to throw parties up here.  Compare
this to the art camps, who primary are creating works that will get used
once, carted out for environmental concern but are basically scrap when it's
all said and done.  I happen to view music and visual media as art, but
there's a huge difference in expense ratios to keep creating one-off works,
and it doesn't sound like the art grants are given without some justification.
And, it's not like it's free money for all the recognized artists.

And as to some years sucking, and later ones rallying, keep in mind this
is ART.   It's not only highly subjective, but if you're really exploring
your mind and its assumptions, there needs to be freshness in the experience.
The very fact that some people drop out and others join in is part of this
cycle of creativity, down years convince many not to go but others step into
the fray.  Like any exhibit, some will be more successful to some than others.
I'd be surprised if everyone came back saying each year was awesome.  The
only way to be impressed by all art is to not have any taste at all. :)

I sure wouldn't mind if they also supported sound art, but don't really
see what would begin to justify any fuss about not having it.

And no, not going this year, no money, no time, and I have a party to throw
here in SF during that week.  Hope some of you come out. :)  Maybe I'll head
to BRC next year if I find a camp of folks I seem to fit. :)

-R.

      Olympics broadcast regulations


        Source: CCTV.com


        08-06-2008 07:54

*Special Report:*   2008 Beijing Olympic Games
<http://intl.2008.cctv.com/index.shtml>

*CCTV's broadcasting rights*

Due to the International Olympic Committee's regulations on the
broadcasting of Olympic events, China Central Television's rights only
extend to the Chinese mainland. This means none of the CCTV
international channels will be able to broadcast the opening and closing
ceremonies, or any of the live events, from the 2008 Olympic Games.

During this period, CCTV International will broadcast a selection of
news, information, features, interviews, and entertainment programs on
the Olympics, all in strict observance of the IOC's copyright rules.

*CCTV.com's broadcasting rights*

Due to IOC's broadcasting regulations, only netizens in China mainland
and Macau can access videos related to Beijing 2008 Olympic Games via
CCTV.com.

It's recommended that viewers and netizens overseas watch Olympic events
via local RHBs TV networks and their Internet platforms. (e.g. Viewers
and netizens in the U.S. can watch Olympic events via NBC's TV networks
and its webcast)

CCTV.com will do its best to, in the timeliest manner, deliver
Games-related information with news reports featuring rich texts and
photos to every netizen for their support and attention given to CCTV.com.

*Internet rights holders for Beijing 2008 Olympic Games >>*
<http://www.cctv.com/english/20080806/106217.shtml>

k, couple questions:

1) etymology of majike?  Not at all familiar with the word.

2) Isaac, wtf are you talking about?  Is this like a reply from that thread
a month ago with you needing a hundred hot girls at a party to find the
one that'll sleep with you or something?  I mean like, how many do you get
a night?

I mean, yeah, there are fewer women at techno parties in general, and fewer
still at undergrounds, but every party I've been to, there were at least a
couple total hotties, and I've generally found them to be, on average, a
whole lot more interesting than the women I've met at the more mainstream
big clubs.  Of course, maybe I'm not the dynamo that Isaac is, the last
underground I went to was the first time in a while I've been pulled into
the restroom by a couple girls, does that happen all the time at places like
Ruby Skye, or is it just for Isaac?  whatever, I've never noticed much
difference in the options I found relevant at different party spots, except
there a lot more people who fell into the "amazingly annoying" category in
the super popular spots that took time to eliminate.

More relevant to me, I'm looking to have fun, in whatever form it takes
for me.  I find more possibilities for fun at techno parties. :)

As to whether Osby's real or not, are we even sure he's in this dimension of
existence?  His quantum probability seems to overlap our own, but that's
about as much as I can say.

-R.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Bassnectar on Burning Man

------=_Part_1266_1625639.1218243994988
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

I think Lorin is right on here.  The sound camps bring a lot of value to the
festival and are a core part of many people's experience.  Countless djs and
sound camp organizers promote for and perform at Burning Man and draw a lot
of people to come.  Burning Man Org receives the revenues from this work and
there aren't even comped tickets for these folks let alone funding?  It
would be one thing if BM was a not for profit event but that is not the
case.

Sure, sound camps do fundraisers.  Which drains the economy of people making
their living in music because all of the djs are expected to perform at
these fund raisers for free or for a small portion of their normal pay.  And
the saturation of these events adversely impacts other events, venues, and
promoters.  Not to mention the fact that this is massive free advertising
for Burning Man.

Saying that Burning Man made Lorin's career seems inaccurate.  Lorin's
innovative production ideas, incredible stage presence, dj skills and
marketing genius made his career.  Try being a random person showing up in
Black Rock City with a bag full of CD's and see if you are traveling the
world next month headlining festivals and large scale events.

When I first started going to Burning Man I never gave any of this stuff
much thought.  It is one of the best parties in the world, I sincerely
believe that.  I'm not a huge magnet dj that people go to the playa to see.
But their stance on the sound camps has me questioning whether I want to
support them.  I believe that the only democracy left is where we choose to
put our dollars.

At the end of the day I will likely go back this year because all of my
friends will be there and it is a great experience.  It feels weird to me
though to know that none of my dollars are going towards the thing that I
enjoy most, and that people who work their asses off for months and months
to build spaces where I have a great time are still required to pay entrance
fees in order to show up and work more.

Sorry for the rant, this is just something I've been thinking about a lot.

Eric Sharp of Rock It Science

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Bassnectar on Burning Man


On Fri, 8 Aug 2008, Rock It Science wrote:
-&e->I think Lorin is right on here.  The sound camps bring a lot of value to the
-&e->festival and are a core part of many people's experience.  Countless djs and
-&e->sound camp organizers promote for and perform at Burning Man and draw a lot
-&e->of people to come.  Burning Man Org receives the revenues from this work and
-&e->there aren't even comped tickets for these folks let alone funding?  It
-&e->would be one thing if BM was a not for profit event but that is not the
-&e->case.

Almost everybody that attends BM is part of a camp, presumably doing 
something of value that propels the overall experience ahead... so where 
would this money come from?  The club/dj/draw model is ridiculous to apply 
to BM.  It costs a lot to get away with BM, that money has to come from 
*somewhere*.  Nobody is selling drinks, and thinking you brought a sound 
system which makes you a "club" while the people who visit your "club" are 
less worthy and therefore should pay more is you just not realizing they 
most likely have a camp somewhere too.  If those other camps went away 
(you know, those non-sound system camps) BM LLC would have a *bear* of a 
time justifying it's existence for 10 seconds... whether you feel it's the 
core of what BM is or not, it needs that "high concept" installation and 
visual art to justify it's not being considered a "lawless week long 
techno party".  What do you think half the yuppies that go tell their 
bosses to get the week off anyway?  It's a fire & arts festival!

-&e->Sure, sound camps do fundraisers.  Which drains the economy of people making
-&e->their living in music because all of the djs are expected to perform at
-&e->these fund raisers for free or for a small portion of their normal pay.  And
-&e->the saturation of these events adversely impacts other events, venues, and
-&e->promoters.  Not to mention the fact that this is massive free advertising
-&e->for Burning Man.

You choose to go to BM, you choose to bring a sound camp.  *shrug*.  Want 
to talk about "draining the economy".  Try looking at it the other way... 
as a local club scene that dies in the weeks coming up to and following 
BM, one of the best weekends to throw a party getting shit on by the 800 
pound gorilla even that a good part of almost every subscene in this town 
attend, etc.  The "drain" is spent on gas, gennies, rv rentals, never to 
be seen in the SF economy again.  When you tip a bartender, they tip a 
barback, who goes to your club, and the circle stays round.  Same thing 
when you pay a DJ, who goes to the store, picks up some gear from 
Robotspeak, etc.  The money you spend on your week @ Burningman just goes 
*poof* pretty much.

If you're not farting excess cash, DON'T GO TO BURNINGMAN or get a grant 
or go work DWP.  Simple.

-&e->Saying that Burning Man made Lorin's career seems inaccurate.  Lorin's
-&e->innovative production ideas, incredible stage presence, dj skills and
-&e->marketing genius made his career.  Try being a random person showing up in
-&e->Black Rock City with a bag full of CD's and see if you are traveling the
-&e->world next month headlining festivals and large scale events.

We took extremes, this probably seems almost as retarded to me as my 
statement seemed to you.  His new album which is supposed to be so "fresh" 
sounds like a ton of glitch hop/british post-nuschool downtempo I heard 
years ago.

-&e->When I first started going to Burning Man I never gave any of this stuff
-&e->much thought.  It is one of the best parties in the world, I sincerely
-&e->believe that.  I'm not a huge magnet dj that people go to the playa to see.
-&e->But their stance on the sound camps has me questioning whether I want to
-&e->support them.  I believe that the only democracy left is where we choose to
-&e->put our dollars.

Ok, so I'll give you a quarter million dollars to spend on whatever you 
want on the playa.  Spend it wisely and justify your decision.  Do you 
really want to pick favorites with an "art form" that seems to be doing 
fine at 100s of sound based camps?  Or maybe bring in some diversity.  
Remember to keep the general populace happy, and also please some of the 
people that were the thrust behind BMORG2.  I'd support a butt rock camp, 
a jazz camp, a light sculpture, a playhouse, a miniature golf course, a 
human petting zoo, an ASSCAR track, etc long before I gave a penny to 
another house/techno/whatever electronic dance music system.  It's 
overrepresented already and difficult to justify funding as most sound 
camps are low concept, not all that artistic and to the untrained ear (and 
maybe even the trained ear) very similar to one another!  Why spend money 
on something that seems to do fine without it... when there are tons of 
artists applying every year for grants to do stuff that has never been 
done before on the playa?

-&e->At the end of the day I will likely go back this year because all of my
-&e->friends will be there and it is a great experience.  It feels weird to me
-&e->though to know that none of my dollars are going towards the thing that I
-&e->enjoy most, and that people who work their asses off for months and months
-&e->to build spaces where I have a great time are still required to pay entrance
-&e->fees in order to show up and work more.

Yeah, weird.  You *can* go and not do a damn thing btw.  BM has screwed it 
up so bad now that "participating" is almost punished.

-&e->Sorry for the rant, this is just something I've been thinking about a lot.
-&e->
-&e->Eric Sharp of Rock It Science

Well written, I just don't agree.  ;)
andyw

Thanks for your comments Andy.  I think we can agree to disagree here.  :)

For those who asked for some back story this is what got my wheels spinning
about the whole thing in the first place.

http://www.opulenttemple.org/archives/000114.php

-Eric Sharp of Rock It Science

On Fri, Aug 8, 2008 at 7:23 PM, AndyW <andy@saturn5.com> wrote:

>
> On Fri, 8 Aug 2008, Rock It Science wrote:
> -&e->I think Lorin is right on here.  The sound camps bring a lot of value
> to the
> -&e->festival and are a core part of many people's experience.  Countless
> djs and
> -&e->sound camp organizers promote for and perform at Burning Man and draw
> a lot
> -&e->of people to come.  Burning Man Org receives the revenues from this
> work and
> -&e->there aren't even comped tickets for these folks let alone funding?
>  It
> -&e->would be one thing if BM was a not for profit event but that is not
> the
> -&e->case.
>
> Almost everybody that attends BM is part of a camp, presumably doing
> something of value that propels the overall experience ahead... so where
> would this money come from?  The club/dj/draw model is ridiculous to apply
> to BM.  It costs a lot to get away with BM, that money has to come from
> *somewhere*.  Nobody is selling drinks, and thinking you brought a sound
> system which makes you a "club" while the people who visit your "club" are
> less worthy and therefore should pay more is you just not realizing they
> most likely have a camp somewhere too.  If those other camps went away
> (you know, those non-sound system camps) BM LLC would have a *bear* of a
> time justifying it's existence for 10 seconds... whether you feel it's the
> core of what BM is or not, it needs that "high concept" installation and
> visual art to justify it's not being considered a "lawless week long
> techno party".  What do you think half the yuppies that go tell their
> bosses to get the week off anyway?  It's a fire & arts festival!
>
> -&e->Sure, sound camps do fundraisers.  Which drains the economy of people
> making
> -&e->their living in music because all of the djs are expected to perform
> at
> -&e->these fund raisers for free or for a small portion of their normal
> pay.  And
> -&e->the saturation of these events adversely impacts other events, venues,
> and
> -&e->promoters.  Not to mention the fact that this is massive free
> advertising
> -&e->for Burning Man.
>
> You choose to go to BM, you choose to bring a sound camp.  *shrug*.  Want
> to talk about "draining the economy".  Try looking at it the other way...
> as a local club scene that dies in the weeks coming up to and following
> BM, one of the best weekends to throw a party getting shit on by the 800
> pound gorilla even that a good part of almost every subscene in this town
> attend, etc.  The "drain" is spent on gas, gennies, rv rentals, never to
> be seen in the SF economy again.  When you tip a bartender, they tip a
> barback, who goes to your club, and the circle stays round.  Same thing
> when you pay a DJ, who goes to the store, picks up some gear from
> Robotspeak, etc.  The money you spend on your week @ Burningman just goes
> *poof* pretty much.
>
> If you're not farting excess cash, DON'T GO TO BURNINGMAN or get a grant
> or go work DWP.  Simple.
>
> -&e->Saying that Burning Man made Lorin's career seems inaccurate.  Lorin's
> -&e->innovative production ideas, incredible stage presence, dj skills and
> -&e->marketing genius made his career.  Try being a random person showing
> up in
> -&e->Black Rock City with a bag full of CD's and see if you are traveling
> the
> -&e->world next month headlining festivals and large scale events.
>
> We took extremes, this probably seems almost as retarded to me as my
> statement seemed to you.  His new album which is supposed to be so "fresh"
> sounds like a ton of glitch hop/british post-nuschool downtempo I heard
> years ago.
>
> -&e->When I first started going to Burning Man I never gave any of this
> stuff
> -&e->much thought.  It is one of the best parties in the world, I sincerely
> -&e->believe that.  I'm not a huge magnet dj that people go to the playa to
> see.
> -&e->But their stance on the sound camps has me questioning whether I want
> to
> -&e->support them.  I believe that the only democracy left is where we
> choose to
> -&e->put our dollars.
>
> Ok, so I'll give you a quarter million dollars to spend on whatever you
> want on the playa.  Spend it wisely and justify your decision.  Do you
> really want to pick favorites with an "art form" that seems to be doing
> fine at 100s of sound based camps?  Or maybe bring in some diversity.
> Remember to keep the general populace happy, and also please some of the
> people that were the thrust behind BMORG2.  I'd support a butt rock camp,
> a jazz camp, a light sculpture, a playhouse, a miniature golf course, a
> human petting zoo, an ASSCAR track, etc long before I gave a penny to
> another house/techno/whatever electronic dance music system.  It's
> overrepresented already and difficult to justify funding as most sound
> camps are low concept, not all that artistic and to the untrained ear (and
> maybe even the trained ear) very similar to one another!  Why spend money
> on something that seems to do fine without it... when there are tons of
> artists applying every year for grants to do stuff that has never been
> done before on the playa?
>
> -&e->At the end of the day I will likely go back this year because all of
> my
> -&e->friends will be there and it is a great experience.  It feels weird to
> me
> -&e->though to know that none of my dollars are going towards the thing
> that I
> -&e->enjoy most, and that people who work their asses off for months and
> months
> -&e->to build spaces where I have a great time are still required to pay
> entrance
> -&e->fees in order to show up and work more.
>
> Yeah, weird.  You *can* go and not do a damn thing btw.  BM has screwed it
> up so bad now that "participating" is almost punished.
>
> -&e->Sorry for the rant, this is just something I've been thinking about a
> lot.
> -&e->
> -&e->Eric Sharp of Rock It Science
>
> Well written, I just don't agree.  ;)
> andyw

Yo peeps, hope you can make it out to Temple tonight.  Justin is gonna
destroy it!  The last show we did there with Green Velvet was incredible.

.dotbleep Invades San Francisco!

Lineup:

Justin Long (.dotbleep, Classic, Chicago)
Tari of Trademarq (.dotbleep, Classic, Denver)
Homero Espinosa (Yerba Buena Discos)
Eric Sharp (Rock It Science, Flavor Group)
Mario Dubbz (Movement, Funk Lab)
Ladyhaus (Phonic)

Snag cheap tickets and skip the line:  http://www.going.com/dotbleepsf

Hope to see you there!

-The Rock It Science Team

Here we proudly introduce .dotbleep recordings. Chicago's hottest new talent
Justin Long, heir to the Derrick Carter Windy City house throne, brings you
the latest and freshest sounds to blow out of this famous city.



You have to have been doing some serious staying in not to have noticed that
Justin has been smashing clubs all over the world with his DJing skills.
His hot, fresh productions impressed 2020 Vison so much that they decided to
join forces with him to create .dotbleep. The best platform to showcase
Justin's productions was a label dedicated to his sound reflecting the
jackin' sound of nu-skool Chicago house and techno music.



Not since Green Velvet aka Cajmere has music sounded so fresh, Chicago's new
generation giving the old hands a run for their money!

------=_Part_1280_15333412.1218307028767--

 international supastars. Partygoers range from electronic music loving

Qool(taken from press release)

One of the best clubbing nights in the world starts at 5pm. Itâs
 called Qool, and it's the original clubbing happy hour in San Francisco,
 if not the world. Every Wednesday evening Jondi & Spesh host a five
 hour club night at the now infamous 111 Minna Art Gallery. The music has
 a progressive theme, from progressive house to breaks to techno, trance
 and even drum 'n bass. Each dj plays a short 45 minute set, and the
 talent ranges from bedroom DJs to international superstars like Seb
 Fontaine, Scott Bond and Lee Coombs.

QoÃ¶l began as function over form â in the early 90âs Spesh had
 bailed out of a high profile residency due to his refusal to play cheesy
 records (it was during this time that Jondi & Spesh produced their first
 tracks together), but soon missed the frequent djing. But with a full
 time job and production work on top of it, the time just wasnât
 there. The solution? Play records once a week right after work at a nearby
 art gallery. With only 6 people on average milling about the space,
 Spesh was definitely in it just to hear the music with his own ears (it is
 worth noting that at this point, Jondi was questioning Speshâs
 sanity). For months, Spesh showed up each week with his records, sometimes
 joined by other djs, and slowly the audience grew.

Nowadays, what began simply as a place for Spesh to spin tracks every
 week on his own terms became a place for hundreds of people to be
 clubbers on their own terms. The patrons of QoÃ¶l, known as QoÃ¶lios, know
 what they want and religiously show up week after week to get it.

QoÃ¶lâs most distinguishing characteristic is its vibe, a downright
 great feeling that builds into a contained fury of waving arms and
 ecstatic dancing every week. In fact its energy has been compared more than
 once to some of historyâs most revered club nights. Most recently
 Jonathan Lisle of Bedrock had this to say of his encounter with QoÃ¶l,
 âWe walked in at 7pm on a Wednesday night and I had the same feeling I
 had when I walked into the Hacienda in Manchester 12 years ago and when
 I walked in Renaissance in Mansfield in 1992. The place was
 electric.â

Now in its 8th year the story continues. Look closely through your
 record box and you will find that some of QoÃ¶lâs resident DJs have
 produced some of your favorite music on Bedrock, SAW, Renaissance, Bedrock
 Breaks, Kubist, Dorigen, and more.

Begin forwarded message:

> According to Adbusters' piece, Hipster: The Dead End of Western  
> Civilization, "We've reached a point in our civilization where  
> counterculture has mutated into a self-obsessed aesthetic vacuum,"  
> and hipsterdom, "the end product of all prior countercultures,"  
> represents nothing short of "the end of Western civilization."
>
> In a certain way, they might be on to something. "Counterculture,"  
> as the construct we, and Adbusters, have known it to be, is  
> disappearing. Maybe gone. If mass and niche culture can meet each  
> other in the middle and make room for both sides, what is there to  
> be "counter" to? More...
>

"No wonder kids grow up crazy," the midget says. "A cat's cradle is  
nothing but a bunch of X's between somebody's hands, and little kids  
look and look and look at all those X's..."
"And?"
"No damn cat, and no damn cradle."
-Kurt Vonnegut

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of  
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will  
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

They even made a movie about it in 1981!

http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0082252/

I think the article makes a good point though:

>    The source of future youth movements will just as likely be the rage, 
> desperation, and hope transmitted from the medinas, favelas, and shanty 
> cities of the southern hemisphere. According to a 2005 report commissioned 
> by the National Research Council and the Institute of Medicine on trends 
> affecting youth in developing countries, there are currently 1.5 billion 
> ten- to twenty-four-year-olds on Earth, and 86 percent of them live in a 
> developing country. In many places in Asia and Africa, this generation is 
> the first generation of teenagers their countries have known. As their 
> economic and political power grows, new sounds, movements, and ideas 
> will grow, too.
>
>    This is where the new youth cultures will be.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Fwd: new post up: "the end of counterculture"

What's mainstream?

3 completely separate "counter-culture" businesses, porn, video games,
and the skateboarding industry* all generate revenue that is the
equivalent to, or greater than, the annual revenues of "mainstream"
Hollywood.

I posit that the good, Christian, go to church on Sunday folk are the
true minority in this country, since they are outnumbered by a ratio
of 4 to 1, since only 20% of Americans even bother to go to Church
anymore.

The problem is is that the majority hasn't woken up to the fact that
they are in the minority.

IE, another way of stating this is what the so-called mainstream
labels as the 'counter-culture', when taken as a whole, is, in fact,
*the* culture in this country.

If only we could get our shit, and money, together and get organized
at the level of say the evangelicals and/or Rush Limbaugh's 20 million
listeners are then we might begin to assert ourselves.

When Tim Russert died the mainstream media had themselves a little
circle-jerk over his passing and shortly thereafter when George Carlin
died he was characterized and marginalized as a counter-cultural icon
and nothing more. I posit the opposite is true, that George Carlin
spoke for, and reflected the beliefs of, far more Americans than that
Russert clown could have ever hoped to.

The thing that bothers me most is what a stranglehold these people
have on public morality in a country where 1 in 5 kids is born out of
wedlock and over 50% of marriages end in divorce. It took until Ronald
Reagan was elected in 1980 for a politician at the national level who
had been divorced to be acceptable. And even today we view a long term
marriage as some sort of hallmark of virtue when the truth is it's got
just as much to do with luck as anything else.

Who are these people who think they are the majority to dictate what's
right and wrong and why does anybody pay them least bit of attention?

~Nyc

* I was skeptical about the skateboard thing myself, but here's the
cite: http://www.forbes.com/forbes/2004/0705/098.html

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR:  Fwd: new post up: "the end of counterculture"

For those interested in this thread I highly recommend Thomas Frank's book *The Conquest of Cool*.  See http://www.press.uchicago.edu/Misc/Chicago/259919.html  

Also worth a read are Heath and Potter's *Nation of Rebels* and Ken Goffman's (aka R.U. Sirius) book *Counterculture Through the Ages*.

Peter

----- Original Message ----
From: Nyc Labrets <digitalcomponents@gmail.com>
To: Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org>
Cc: SFRaves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Monday, August 18, 2008 6:17:25 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Fwd: new post up: "the end of counterculture"

What's mainstream?

3 completely separate "counter-culture" businesses, porn, video games,
and the skateboarding industry* all generate revenue that is the
equivalent to, or greater than, the annual revenues of "mainstream"
Hollywood.

I posit that the good, Christian, go to church on Sunday folk are the
true minority in this country, since they are outnumbered by a ratio
of 4 to 1, since only 20% of Americans even bother to go to Church
anymore.

The problem is is that the majority hasn't woken up to the fact that
they are in the minority.

IE, another way of stating this is what the so-called mainstream
labels as the 'counter-culture', when taken as a whole, is, in fact,
*the* culture in this country.

If only we could get our shit, and money, together and get organized
at the level of say the evangelicals and/or Rush Limbaugh's 20 million
listeners are then we might begin to assert ourselves.

When Tim Russert died the mainstream media had themselves a little
circle-jerk over his passing and shortly thereafter when George Carlin
died he was characterized and marginalized as a counter-cultural icon
and nothing more. I posit the opposite is true, that George Carlin
spoke for, and reflected the beliefs of, far more Americans than that
Russert clown could have ever hoped to.

The thing that bothers me most is what a stranglehold these people
have on public morality in a country where 1 in 5 kids is born out of
wedlock and over 50% of marriages end in divorce. It took until Ronald
Reagan was elected in 1980 for a politician at the national level who
had been divorced to be acceptable. And even today we view a long term
marriage as some sort of hallmark of virtue when the truth is it's got
just as much to do with luck as anything else.

Who are these people who think they are the majority to dictate what's
right and wrong and why does anybody pay them least bit of attention?

~Nyc

* I was skeptical about the skateboard thing myself, but here's the
cite: http://www.forbes.com/forbes/2004/0705/098.html

That's kinda what I was talking about...  what was counter culture is 
now mainstream, and what was mainstream has become counter culture.

Much in the way that at some parties and events i go to I'm the only 
person there without any ink.  I'm the odd ball that's outside of the norm.

It's all a matter of perspective.  mainstream vs counterculture is 
really more about where you personally stand.  Hip Hop is very 
mainstream and was one of the biggest counter cultures to rise up out of 
the late 20th century (doubt anyone wants to argue it wasn't).  Things 
change, they flip flop, the pendulum will continue to swing.  People are 
destined to eventually become that which they hate.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Fwd: new post up: "the end of counterculture"

I think you have to look at why counter-cultures are created in the  
first place.  Counter culture seems to be a term that is applied only  
to non-mainstream thinking groups from about 1950 on, but there have  
been many more than that.  The difference from 1950 on is you have  
Madison Ave. and you have television.  How heavily do these factors  
weigh in to single these groups out to get perhaps more attention  
than they deserve, or perhaps the wrong kind of attention?  I would  
venture to say that raves get a particularly bad rap from these  
forces, yet they live on.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: The Fingermonsters @ Down Like This - Thursday 8.28.08

Thursday, August 28th
Down Like This @ Temple (66 Natoma St entrance)
No Cover

Catacombs:

The Fingermonsters (Monsta Music) - Live PA!
Tycho Swan
Swing

Destiny Lounge:

Disco Night!!!
DJs TBA

The Fingermonsters Bio:

The Fingermonsters consist of George Cochrane, Cubik, Andrew Phelan and
Shawn Allen, four friends working together out of San Francisco's famed
Moulton Studios complex. Between their various solo careers and
collaborations, these four have had album and EPs out on labels such as
Amenti, Body Rhythm, Dinner Party, Drop Music, Eight-Tracks, Prismatic, So
Sound and Wide Hive. Together as The Fingermonsters, the four produce a
unique mix of big room tech house, breaks, minimal, and electro. Their live
PA is a site to behold, with all four members freaking out together onstage
on a variety of synths, drum machines, laptops, and general insanity. More
on the Fingermonsters and their label Monsta Music can be found on the site
of their label group, www.prismatictracks.com.

> The Fingermonsters Bio:
>
> The Fingermonsters consist of George Cochrane, Cubik, Andrew Phelan and
> Shawn Allen, four friends working together out of San Francisco's famed
> Moulton Studios complex. Between their various solo careers and
> collaborations, these four have had album and EPs out on labels such as
> Amenti, Body Rhythm, Dinner Party, Drop Music, Eight-Tracks, Prismatic, So
> Sound and Wide Hive. Together as The Fingermonsters, the four produce a
> unique mix of big room tech house, breaks, minimal, and electro. Their live
> PA is a site to behold, with all four members freaking out together onstage
> on a variety of synths, drum machines, laptops, and general insanity. More
> on the Fingermonsters and their label Monsta Music can be found on the site
> of their label group, www.prismatictracks.com.
>

An old friend has passed:


We'd been sitting on the sad news that Tina L'Hotsky had died, hoping =20=

that it was just another rumor of her death and we'd hear from her =20
again as we have done every half-decade or so, like clockwork. But =20
it's dawned on us now that this time it's true. We first heard she was =20=

dead (from cancer, of course) in an "I'm told" item in Michael Musto's =20=

La Daily Musto blog three days ago (since updated with the Official =20
Death Notice!) and have spent the days between then and now trying to =20=

locate clips of stories we'd written about her during New York's =20
downtown heyday when we had an enormous crush on her and she was the =20
luminous, self-proclaimed Queen of the Mudd Club (which no one =20
disputed). "Queen" may have been just a ceremonial title, but it was =20
only one of her careers back then; she was also a super-8 filmmaker, =20
an actress, a writer, an artist, and a driving creative force inside =20
the Mudd at the end of the '70s, which, we had no way of knowing then, =20=

would really start something. Tina L'Hotsky =96 yes, her real name =96 =
was =20
beautiful, funny, ironic, mysterious, and as secretly tragic as a =20
heroine in a 19th-century novel. Now, sadly, we seem to have misplaced =20=

all our Tina souvenirs but this uncredited photo taken, we're =20
guessing, around 1980. And this note dated December, 2006: "I'm =20
writing the Queen of the Mudd Club book. Kisses, Tina."

http://worldofwonder.net/archives/2008/Aug/20/tinalhotsky.wow





Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

The US is:  "...a nation of 200 million used-car salesmen with all the =20=

money we need to buy guns and no qualms about killing anybody else in =20=

the world who tries to make us uncomfortable."
-Hunter S. Thompson

"Friend, hope for the truth while you are alive.  Jump into experience =20=

while you are alive!  What you call "salvation" belongs to the time =20
before death.  If you don't break your ropes while you are alive, do =20
you think ghosts will do it after?"
-Kabir





--Boundary_(ID_0n8d3UrG2NxMANFpyi5yqQ)--

From: "Daniel Faustine" <DFaustine@procedesoftware.com>
To: <SFRaves@hyperreal.org>
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: RE: [sfraves] NRR: Fwd: new post up: "the end of counterculture"

IMHO, The only real revolution left that has any real potential to
change society is monetary. American culture is deeply, and some would
argue irrevocably, mired in its capitalism and advertising. A lot of
people don't know the difference between expression and consumption --
i.e. they buy things that symbolize their uniqueness, and try to fill
voids in their lives by going shopping for more crap.

What would happen if people just stopped spending money? Obviously that
isn't possible... but I think all we really have to do to make a
difference is be more conscious of how we spend the money we have. Our
money is our only real voice in this society. Ask questions about the
goods you buy. Where did this come from? More importantly, do I really
need this?

You want to be a part of the REAL counterculture? Go start a commune in
Mendocino, grow your own food, make your own clothes and fuel, and
invent yourself some new forms of entertainment.

Thanks for indulging me. I know to some extent I'm preaching to the
choir here.

Rave on.

-Dan=20
-----Original Message-----
From: Nyc Labrets [mailto:digitalcomponents@gmail.com]=20
Sent: Monday, August 18, 2008 6:17 PM
To: Apollo
Cc: SFRaves@hyperreal.org
Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Fwd: new post up: "the end of
counterculture"

What's mainstream?

3 completely separate "counter-culture" businesses, porn, video games,
and the skateboarding industry* all generate revenue that is the
equivalent to, or greater than, the annual revenues of "mainstream"
Hollywood.

I posit that the good, Christian, go to church on Sunday folk are the
true minority in this country, since they are outnumbered by a ratio
of 4 to 1, since only 20% of Americans even bother to go to Church
anymore.

The problem is is that the majority hasn't woken up to the fact that
they are in the minority.

IE, another way of stating this is what the so-called mainstream
labels as the 'counter-culture', when taken as a whole, is, in fact,
*the* culture in this country.

If only we could get our shit, and money, together and get organized
at the level of say the evangelicals and/or Rush Limbaugh's 20 million
listeners are then we might begin to assert ourselves.

When Tim Russert died the mainstream media had themselves a little
circle-jerk over his passing and shortly thereafter when George Carlin
died he was characterized and marginalized as a counter-cultural icon
and nothing more. I posit the opposite is true, that George Carlin
spoke for, and reflected the beliefs of, far more Americans than that
Russert clown could have ever hoped to.

The thing that bothers me most is what a stranglehold these people
have on public morality in a country where 1 in 5 kids is born out of
wedlock and over 50% of marriages end in divorce. It took until Ronald
Reagan was elected in 1980 for a politician at the national level who
had been divorced to be acceptable. And even today we view a long term
marriage as some sort of hallmark of virtue when the truth is it's got
just as much to do with luck as anything else.

Who are these people who think they are the majority to dictate what's
right and wrong and why does anybody pay them least bit of attention?

~Nyc

* I was skeptical about the skateboard thing myself, but here's the
cite: http://www.forbes.com/forbes/2004/0705/098.html

Subject: [sfraves] burning man music experiment, location

http://gilesbowkett.blogspot.com/2008/08/where-to-find-me-at-burning-man.html

software-generated ambient music running continually for hours.

also doing a variable-tempo live AI drumming "laptop DJ" (not) set
which could very easily suck ass. thought I was going to have
basslines finished by now. maybe I can hack it in motels on the drive
up. the cool part is you start at a slow tempo and can take it as far
as jungle very easily.

despite bragging I may have done in past the system is pretty
bare-bones; the ambient autonomous version can do key changes,
samples, simple harmony and extremely simple basslines. I may be able
to cannibalize this code to give a Bukem-style set of pads and
basslines to the live danceable set also.

actually, that would be fucking awesome. add in a chord progression
framework on top of the key changes and you would totally have
something.

OK. doing a variable-tempo live AI drumming "laptop DJ" (not) set
which may totally suck ass and may be totally fucking awesome.
